<DOC><DOCNO> AP890911-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1703EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Drexel-Chronology     09-11 0727</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Drexel-Chronology,0761</SECOND><HEAD>Rundown of Key Events in Drexel Investigation</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Drexel Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here is a chronology of major developments in the governmentinvestigation of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.   Nov. 14, 1986 _ Speculator Ivan Boesky agrees to pay a $100million penalty to settle charges of trading on inside information.He agrees to cooperate in a probe of Drexel, its top financierMichael Milken and others.   April 23, 1987 _ Boesky pleads guilty to a single charge ofconspiracy to lie to the Securities and Exchange Commission,punishable by five years imprisonment and a $250,000 fine.   Dec. 18, 1987 _ Boesky is sentenced to a three-year prison termand no fine.   March 24, 1988 _ Boesky begins serving sentence at aminimum-security facility in Lompoc, Calif.   Aug. 4, 1988 _ A grand jury indicts five partners in theinvestment concern Princeton-Newport Partners and former Drexeltrader Bruce Newberg over an alleged tax fraud scheme, thefirst-ever racketeering charges against securities professionals.Defense lawyers call it a blackmail tactic to pressure defendantsinto testifying against Milken, Drexel and others.   Sept. 7, 1988 _ The SEC accuses Drexel, Milken and three otheremployees of violating a wide range of securities laws, most inconnection with Boesky.   Dec. 6, 1988 _ Cary Maultasch, a senior Drexel trader accused inthe SEC case and threatened with numerous indictments, turns state'sevidence in a plea-bargain agreement with the government.   Dec. 7, 1988 _ Princeton Newport Partners liquidates because ofwhat lawyers for its indicted parters call brutal government misuseof the racketeering laws to coerce them into cooperating in theDrexel investigation.   Dec. 21, 1988 _ Reversing earlier assertions of innocence, Drexelagrees to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a record $650 millionin fines and restitution to settle what became the biggestsecurities fraud probe in history. Milken continues to assertinnocence.   Jan. 25, 1989 _ The government files formal charges againstDrexel, publicly detailing for the first time the accusations towhich it will plead guilty. Most stem from the firm's allegedrelationship with Boesky.   March 10, 1989 _ Drexel reportedly agrees to ban Milken for lifefrom the firm and prevent other employees from talking business withhim under a proposed settlement with the SEC.   March 22, 1989 _ Drexel trader Lisa Jones is convicted of lyingto a grand jury, the first perjury conviction in the Drexel case.   March 29, 1989 _ A grand jury indicts Milken, brother LowellMilken and former Drexel trader Bruce Newberg on 98 counts ofracketeering and fraud. Potential penalties and fines could exceed$12 billion plus long prison terms.   April 7, 1989 _ The Milkens plead innocent.   April 13, 1989 _ Drexel settles civil fraud case with the SEC,under terms that subject the firm to unprecedented federalmonitoring for three years and force it to sever ties with MichaelMilken.   April 25, 1980 _ Newberg pleads innocent.   April 26, 1989 _ A judge rejects Boesky's petition for earlyrelease from prison.   June 15, 1989 _ Michael Milken resigns after 19 years at Drexelto form his own consulting firm called International Capital AccessGroup. Lowell Milken quits to return to practicing law.   July 31, 1989 _ Princeton-Newport defendants are found guilty,signaling that juries are capable of understanding complicatedsecurities-fraud allegations and are willing to convict under thepunitive racketeering laws.   Aug. 23, 1989 _ Jones is sentenced to 18 months in prison andordered to pay more than $50,000 in fines and prison costs.   Aug. 30, 1989 _ Drexel announces several high-level managementchanges including the appointment of a new president, designed tostrengthen what the firm calls its competitive position.   Aug. 31, 1989 _ The Washington Post discloses a confidential SECmemo detailing what the agency claims was a secret July 1986 meetingbetween Boesky and Milken aimed at concealing a $5.3 million paymentthat is believed to be the heart of the government's case againstMilken.   Sept. 7, 1989 _ After months of challenges and legal delays,Drexel and federal prosecutors reach a final agreement on the guiltyplea. The breakthrough comes after the government drops a demandthat Drexel withhold Milken's 1988 compensation of more than $100million.   Sept. 11, 1989 _ Drexel pleads guilty to six felonies and beginsthe payment of more than $650 million as punishment.</TEXT></DOC>